alerts.title: Beach Hazards Statement
regions: Coastal North Bay Including Point Reyes National Seashore
Southern Monterey Bay and Big Sur Coast
alerts.description: ...SOUTHERLY SWELL GENERATED BY HURRICANE SERGIO WILL MOVE INTO THE SURF ZONE AND COASTAL WATERS LATER THIS WEEK... ...BEACH HAZARDS STATEMENT IN EFFECT FROM LATE WEDNESDAY NIGHT THROUGH FRIDAY AFTERNOON... The National Weather Service in San Francisco has issued a Beach Hazards Statement for increased risk of rip currents, sneaker waves, longshore current, and breaking waves which is in effect from late Wednesday night through Friday afternoon. * WAVES AND SURF...Southerly swell 4 to 6 feet with a period of 14 to 17 seconds. Breaking waves of up to 10 feet will be possible at favored locations. * HAZARDS...Increased risk of rip currents and sneaker waves, stronger longshore current at west facing beaches, and somewhat larger breaking waves at south to southwest facing beaches. * TIMING...6am Thursday through 6pm Friday. * LOCATION...Primarily south to southwest facing coastal sections from Monterey county northward through Sonoma county. Including but not limited to...Stinson Beach...Carmel Beach... Santa Cruz Boardwalk Beach and Twin Lakes Beach. * POTENTIAL IMPACTS...Increased risk of sneaker waves and rip currents at these beaches. Unsuspecting beach-goers may suddenly be pulled out to sea. Never turn your back to the ocean!
